    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-10-06T20:48:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-10-06T20:48:00-05:00" n="237"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d237">
                <head>237. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Congo</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d237fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 770G.00/9–2660. Secret; Limit Distribution. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_FCVJ1">Ferguson</persName> and Woodruff, cleared in draft
                        with Wallner and Chadbourn, and approved by <persName corresp="#p_PJK1"
                            >Penfield</persName>. Repeated to <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>,
                        Brussels, and Elisabethville.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-10-06T20:48:00">October 6, 1960, 8:48
                            p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1009. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 824, rptd New York 157, Brussels
                        341.<note n="1" xml:id="d237fn1">
                        <ref target="#d229">Document 229</ref>.</note> Following démarche reported
                        <gloss target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss> Department would appreciate your
                    views on following subsequent steps which might be taken: <persName
                        corresp="#p_KJ8">Kasavubu</persName> and other appropriate Congo leaders
                    might be approached and informed, while Department considers round-table
                    conference useful, we hope focus this gathering will be preliminary
                    constitutional talks, not settlement <persName corresp="#p_LP3"
                        >Lumumba</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_KJ8">Kasavubu</persName> dispute
                    or composition executive branch <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss>. Whole
                    assumption <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> should be <persName
                        corresp="#p_LP3">Lumumba</persName> government now legally out of office. We
                    hope <persName corresp="#p_KJ8">Kasavubu</persName> will host conference and
                    welcome delegates and <persName corresp="#p_IJ1">Ileo</persName> or <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJM2">Bomboko</persName> chair session from then on. Obviously
                    round table should include widest feasible spread Congo opinion and include
                    parliamentary leaders and some <gloss target="#t_MNC1">MNC</gloss>–<persName
                        corresp="#p_LP3">Lumumba</persName>.</p>
                <p>Department also considers it important Tshombe attend conference, and
                    Elisabethville might do what it can influence him this direction. We hope he
                    will be able come forward with specific ideas about Katanga contribution <gloss
                        target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> revenue to assist urgent rehabilitation
                    measures such fields as public health and refugee relief. Department feels this
                    would win him some points African states as well as facilitate US and <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> funding problems for <gloss target="#t_ONUC1"
                        >ONUC</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dillon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
